Part I - Project - Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Xinyi Liao¶

Introduction¶

The data consists of information regarding the rides taken in February, 2019, within the Ford GoBike System of the greater San Francisco Bay area. The data contains attributes, including details such as duration, start and end times, station locations, user type, and demographic information of the trips.

Data Cleaning¶

Issue 1. start_time, end_time, user_type, member_gender are str¶

Define: Convert date columns to datetime, and convert categorical columns to their proper data type¶

Code¶

In [7]:
df_trips = biketrips.copy()
df_trips['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_trips['start_time'])
df_trips['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_trips['end_time'])

df_trips['user_type'] = df_trips['user_type'].astype('category')
df_trips['member_gender'] = df_trips['member_gender'].astype('category')
df_trips['bike_share_for_all_trip'] = df_trips['bike_share_for_all_trip'].astype('category')

Define: Set low limit as 1919, and replace any value below with NaN, then create a new member_age column¶

In [11]:
df_trips.loc[df_trips['member_birth_year'] < 1919, 'member_birth_year'] = np.nan

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

After cleaning, the dataset contains 174880 trips without null values, and 20 columns. They can be concluded as following:

  • trip info: start/end_time, start/end_day, start/end_hr, bike_id, duration_hrs, bike_share_for_all_trip
  • member info: user_type, member_gender, member_age
  • station info: start/end_station_id, start/end_station_name, start/end_station_latitude, start/end_station_longitude

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in what features are the best to identify common usage patterns.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Examining patterns in usage over different time periods, such as start/end hr, days in a week, and difference between subscribers and customers. The start or end station names are also helpful to explore which areas are busiest. Also gender,and age can provide insights to better understand the user base.

# Create function to spot places where repeat code is.
def plot_labels(title, x_axis, y_axis):
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(x_axis)
    plt.ylabel(y_axis)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)

# convert start/end day into ordered categorical types
ordinal_var_dict = {'start_day': ['Sunday', 'Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday', 'Saturday'],
                    'end_day': ['Sunday', 'Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday', 'Saturday']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    df_trips[var] = df_trips[var].astype(ordered_var)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

In terms of time duration of the trips, almost 99% of them are short and fast trips, despite of the outliers > 20 hrs. Majority of the trips are between 0.1 hr - 0.2 hr (6 mins - 12 mins). In user components, 90% of the users are subscribers, 75% are male, and age range is between 25 and 40. From the top 5 start and end stations with most trip counts, Market St at 10th St, San Francisco Caltrain, and BART Station are the busiest and all at downtown area. The amount of trips reached its peak at8 a.m. and 17 p.m. during the day, with business days (Mon-Fri) having more trips than weekends.

There is no particular transformation for the dataset, but need to remind the outliers in duration_hr.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Due the outliers in duration_hr, the first plot for the distribution doesn't look nice and is very right-tailed. By setting the largest percertile to 99.5% in .describle(), we can see that 99.5% of the trips are below 2 hrs. Thus, for further visualizations, I need to set the limit as 2 hours to exclude the outliers.

start_hr and end_hr are highly correlated, but we can see some outliers points lie between 15hr and 20 hr. Surprisingly, start_hr and end_hr have a a very weak positive correlation with member_age. member_age and duration_hrs don't have any strong relationships with any other numeric variables. And in any scatter plots with duration_hrs, we can see the outliers very clearly.

From the two barplots above, subscriber usage obviously rises during typical rush hours at 8 a.m. and 5 p.m. during business days. But we cannot see the clear usage pattern from the customers, but similarly they use mostly on rush hours and Thursday.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Since most of users like to have short trips, start_hr and end_hr have strong positive correlation. But other numeric variables do not have any strong relationship with each other. And we need to set the upper bound for the duration_hrs. The usage pattern between subscribers and customers are very different. Subscribers mostly rent the bikes for work commute purpose. There is no clear pattern for customers, they might use the bike for random or casual trips since they only accounted for 9.5% in user base.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Customers tend to have longer distance trips than Subscribers.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • The difference in trip duration between customers and subscribers becomes more evident when analyzed across different days of the week. Customers generally have longer trips regardless of the day, with the longest trips on weekends. Subscribers have shorter trips overall, but with a slight increase in trip duration on weekends.
  • The majority of trips are taken during the weekdays, with the highest counts on Thursdays and Tuesdays. Subscribers use the service more frequently than customers, and the male subscriber group has the highest trip counts.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The trip duration patterns across genders are more pronounced when considering user type. Among customers, female users tend to have longer trips than males and other genders. However, among subscribers, male users have the shortest trip duration range, which is an interesting observation.

Conclusions¶

  • Trip durations were mostly short, with a majority of trips lasting less than an hour. The distribution was positively skewed, indicating that riders generally prefer short, quick trips.
  • Subscribers made up a significant portion of the user base. Males were the predominant gender among both user types. Customers tend to have longer trips than subscribers
  • The analysis of trip counts by day of the week revealed that the service was used more heavily during weekdays, with Thursdays and Tuesdays having the highest usage. This suggests that the service is popular among commuters for work-related trips.
  • The top five start and end stations were all located in downtown San Francisco, indicating that the service is particularly popular in areas with high foot traffic and convenient access to other modes of transportation.
  • Female customers having the longest trip durations on average. Among subscribers, male users had the shortest trip durations.
